Strikeout Home/Away Effects

Jim Albert

7/19/2017

The Problem and Multilevel Model

Interested in learning about the strikeout rates of baseball players and how strikeout rates vary between home and away games. We know there is a positive home field effect, but we wonder if the size of the effect varies across players.

Suppose that \(y_{ij}\) denotes the number of strikeouts in \(n_{ij}\) at-bats of the \(i\)th player in the \(j\)th situation (\(j = 1, 2\) for home and away).

The multilevel model: \[ y_{ij} \sim Binom(n_{ij}, p_{ij}) \]

\[ logit \, \, p_{ij} = \mu + \eta_i + \delta_i \times (HOME = j) \] \[ \eta_i \sim N(0, \sigma_1), \, \, \delta_j \sim N(0, \sigma_2) \]

where \((\mu, \sigma_1, \sigma_2)\) are given “vague priors”

The random effect \(\eta_i\) represents the strikeout “ability” of the \(i\)th player and \(\delta_i\) represents the ability of the \(i\) player to do better during home games.

The Data and Initial Exploration

Get strikeout data for all players in 2016 season for home and away games from Retrosheet play-by-play files.

load("~/Google Drive/Retrosheet/pbp.2016.Rdata")

Need some packages:

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(rstanarm)
library(bayesplot)
d2016 %>% filter(AB_FL == TRUE) %>%
  select(BAT_ID, BAT_HOME_ID, EVENT_CD) %>%
  mutate(K = EVENT_CD == 3) -> d

Limit to players with at least 300 at-bats:

S0 <- summarize(group_by(d, BAT_ID), AB=n())
inner_join(d, S0) %>% filter(AB >= 300) -> d

Collect home and away K data:

S <- summarize(group_by(d, BAT_ID, BAT_HOME_ID),
               N = n(),
               y = sum(K),
               z = N - y)

Do an exploratory plot. Here I compute the logits of the estimated probabilities of strikeout for home and away games. Graph the mean logit against the (HOME - AWAY) difference. On average, one would expect batters to do better at home games, so the mean logit difference is negative.

S1 <- inner_join(filter(S, BAT_HOME_ID==0),
                 filter(S, BAT_HOME_ID==1),
                 by="BAT_ID")
S1 <- mutate(S1,
             logit.x=log(y.x / z.x),
             logit.y=log(y.y / z.y))

Fit Multilevel Model on Stan

The modeling frunction is stan_glmer which has a similar syntax to the familiar glmer function. This indicates that both the intercepts and the slopes are varying across players and follow a bivariate normal distribution. By indicating family=logit, by default a logistic link will be used.

bfit <- stan_glmer(cbind(y, z) ~ 
                   (1 + BAT_HOME_ID | BAT_ID),
                   data=S,
                   family=binomial)

We load the output bfit from previous MCMC run. By use of the as.array function, we convert the output into a simulated array where the dimensions correspond to simulation, chain, parameter.

load("homefit.Rdata")
posterior <- as.array(bfit)

The prior_summary function gives information about the default priors chosen.

prior_summary(bfit)
## Priors for model 'bfit' 
## ------
## Intercept (after predictors centered)

## 
## Covariance
##  ~ decov(reg. = 1, conc. = 1, shape = 1, scale = 1)

Graphs of the Posterior

First define a particular theme element for drawing the title.

TH <- theme(
  plot.title = element_text(
    colour = "blue",
    size = 18,
    hjust = 0.5,
    vjust = 0.8,
    angle = 0
  )
)

Some work to get indices of parameters of interest:

posterior[, , c(492, 494)] <-
  sqrt(posterior[, , c(492, 494)])
intercept_indices <- seq(2, 490, by=2)
slope_indices <- seq(3, 491, by=2)
attr(posterior, "dimnames")[[3]][intercept_indices] <-
        paste('a', 1:245, sep="")
attr(posterior, "dimnames")[[3]][slope_indices] <-
  paste('b', 1:245, sep="")
attr(posterior, "dimnames")[[3]][c(492, 494)] <-
  c("SD_a", "SD_b")
var_names <- attr(posterior, "dimnames")[[3]]

We show the posterior densities for a few of the intercept parameters (the person effects).

mcmc_areas(posterior, pars=var_names[seq(2, 30, by=2)]) +
  ggtitle("Posteriors for Some Intercepts") + TH

Here are graphs of the posterior densities for a few of the slope parameters (the home/away effects).

mcmc_areas(posterior, pars=var_names[seq(3, 31, by=2)]) +
  ggtitle("Posteriors for Some Slopes") + TH

Here are posterior probability intervals for all intercepts:

mcmc_intervals(posterior,
               pars=var_names[intercept_indices]) +
  theme(axis.title.y=element_blank(),
        axis.text.y=element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.y=element_blank()) +
  ggtitle("Posteriors for All Intercepts") + TH

Here are posterior probability intervals for all slopes:

mcmc_intervals(posterior,
               pars=var_names[slope_indices]) +
  theme(axis.title.y=element_blank(),
        axis.text.y=element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.y=element_blank()) +
  ggtitle("Posteriors for All Slopes") + TH

Here are posterior densities for the two random effects standard deviations \(\sigma_1\) and \(\sigma_2\). As one would expect, the variability of the strikeout talents is much larger than the variability of the home/away talents.

mcmc_areas(posterior, pars=var_names[c(492, 494)]) +
  ggtitle("Posteriors for Random Effect SDs") + TH
